@subsection The PointGroup KeyVal Constructor

The @code{PointGroup} KeyVal constructor looks for three keywords:
@code{symmetry}, @code{symmetry_frame}, and @code{origin}. @code{symmetry} is
a string containing the Schoenflies symbol of the point group.  @code{origin}
is an array of doubles which gives the x, y, and z coordinates of the origin
of the symmetry frame.  @code{symmetry_frame} is an array of arrays of
doubles which specify the principal axes for the transformation matrices.

For example, a simple input which will use the default @code{origin} and
@code{symmetry_frame} ((0,0,0) and the unit matrix, respectively), might
look like this:

@example
default: (
  symmetry = "c2v"
)
@end example

Why would you ever want to specify the @code{symmetry_frame}?  By default,
the principal rotation axis is taken to be the z axis.  If you already have
a set of coordinates which assume that the rotation axis is the x axis,
then you'll have to rotate your frame of reference, viz:

@example
default: (
  symmetry = "c2v"
  symmetry_frame = [
    [ 0 0 1 ]
    [ 0 1 0 ]
    [ 1 0 0 ]
  ]
)
@end example

Would you ever want to specify the @code{origin}?  If you can think of a
reason then let me know.


